data_generator.py
      SyntheticDepthDataset outputs a generated dataset of shapes (eclipse or square) on a background mesh

predict.py
      Use a pre-trained model in model path and input image to generate 3D estimation of 2D image of shapes
      uses visualize_pointcloud function from vizualize_depth_matplotlib.py to vizualize pointcloud

vizualize_depth_matplotlib.py
      Provides visualize_pointcloud function for predict.py

train.py:
      Runs the complete traning loop using data from data_generator.py SyntheticDepthDataset class.

      Loop goes like this:

      1. Data generation:
            full_dataset = SyntheticDepthDataset(length=dataset_size, img_size=img_size)
            returns full dataset of fixed size represented PyTorch tensor (torch.Size([3, H, W])):
                  rgb_t[0] = red channel (H × W)
                  rgb_t[1] = green channel (H × W)
                  rgb_t[2] = blue channel (H × W)
      
      2. Patch embedding (tokenisation)
            PatchEmbed() uses Conv2d to embed all patches of the input image with patch size and stride and padding options applied
      
      3. Positional embedding:
            tokens = tokens + self.pos_embed
            potitional vector token is added to raw token from the patch embedding

      4. Transformer block
            A :   class Block(nn.Module) defines how each transformer block.
                  each block performs:
                        normalization (self.ln1/self.ln2 = nn.LayerNorm(n_embd))
                        ln1 for normalization input before self attention is applied
                        ln2 for normalization of the updated tokens before the encoder
            
            B :   Uses multi-head self-attention to allow patches to attend to other patches.

                        self.attention = MultiHeadAttention(n_head, head_size)

            C :   MultiHeadAttention runs multiple attention Heads in parallel.
                  Each Head computes:

                        Attention(Q,K,V) = softmax(QKᵀ / √d) V

                        where Q (queries), K (keys), and V (values) are learned projections of the input tokens.

                        The outputs from all Heads are concatenated and projected back to the embedding dimension.
                  
            D :   Residual connection:
                        x = x + self.attention(self.ln1(x))
                        Token vector is added to the attention output to update specific features of the token vector depending on the assosiation output

            E :   Feed-forward MLP (class Encoder(nn.Module)):
                        x = x + self.encoder(self.ln2(x))
                        After attention is applied, process each token independently

      5. Final normalization after transformation blocks
            tokens = self.ln_f(tokens) = nn.LayerNorm(n_embd)

      6. Reshape image back to 2D:
            feat = tokens.transpose(1, 2).reshape(B, D, h, w)

            The transformer outputs a flat sequence (B, T, n_embd). To use a CNN decoder, this gets reshaped back into a 2D spatial grid (B, n_embd, h, w) which is the same spatial layout as the original patch grid.
      
      7. CNN upsampling (decoder) 
            class ConvDecoder(nn.Module) upscales: 
                  Takes the (B, n_embd, h, w) feature map produced by the transformer and upsamples it back to (B, 1, H, W) using transposed convolutions.

      8. Compute loss and back propagate to update weights:
            
            A: Compute loss:
                  _, loss = model(rgb, depth_gt)

            B: Update weights:
                  loss.backward()
                  optimizer.step()
            
